SIMPLE: shield
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shield
<hw>Shield</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sheld</ets>,
<ets>scheld</ets>, AS. <ets>scield</ets>, <ets>scild</ets>,
<ets>sceld</ets>, <ets>scyld</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>scild</ets>,
OFries. <ets>skeld</ets>, D. & G. <ets>schild</ets>, OHG.
<ets>scilt</ets>, Icel. <ets>skj⟦oum⟧ldr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>sk⟦oum⟧ld</ets>, Dan. <ets>skiold</ets>, Goth. <ets>skildus</ets>;
of uncertain origin. Cf. <er>Sheldrake</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
broad piece of defensive armor, carried on the arm, -- formerly in
general use in war, for the protection of the body. See
<er>Buckler</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now put your <qex>shields</qex> before your hearts and fight,⟦br⟧
With hearts more proof than <qex>shields</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything which protects or defends; defense;
shelter; protection.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My council is my
<xex>shield</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Figuratively, one who protects or defends.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fear not, Abram; I am thy <qex>shield</qex>, and thy exceeding
great reward.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>In lichens, a Hardened cup or disk
surrounded by a rim and containing the fructification, or
asci.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>The escutcheon or field on which
are placed the bearings in coats of arms. Cf.
<er>Lozenge</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mining & Tunneling)</fld> <def>A framework used to
protect workmen in making an adit under ground, and capable of being
pushed along as excavation progresses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A spot resembling, or having the form of, a
shield.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Bespotted as with <xex>shields</xex> of red and
black.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>A coin, the old French crown, or ⟦eacute⟧cu, having
on one side the figure of a shield.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Shield fern</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>any fern of
the genus <gen>Aspidium</gen>, in which the fructifications are covered
with shield-shaped indusia; -- called also <altname>wood
fern</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shield</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shield
<hw>Shield</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Shielded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shielding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>scidan</ets>,
<ets>scyldan</ets>. <ets>See</ets> <er>Shield</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover with, or as with, a shield; to cover from
danger; to defend; to protect from assault or injury.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shouts of applause ran ringing through the field,⟦br⟧
To see the son the vanquished father <qex>shield</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A woman's shape doth <qex>shield</qex> thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To ward off; to keep off or out.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They brought with them their usual weeds, fit to <qex>shield</qex>
the cold to which they had been inured.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To avert, as a misfortune; hence, as a supplicatory
exclamation, forbid!</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God <qex>shield</qex> that it should so befall.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God <qex>shield</qex> I should disturb devotion!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shield-bearer</ent>⟦br⟧
